1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,728
Returning to our example of Sigma equals phi, psi, we

2
00:00:03,828 --> 00:00:06,979
can easily see that this set is not complete.

3
00:00:07,066 --> 00:00:09,785
We see that the natural number line is a model of

4
00:00:09,885 --> 00:00:12,948
Sigma where E is interpreted as the less than relation.

5
00:00:13,066 --> 00:00:16,857
Since for all numbers x, y, z, if x is less than y

6
00:00:16,957 --> 00:00:20,280
and y is less than z, then x is less than z,

7
00:00:20,400 --> 00:00:22,546
and no number is less than itself.

8
00:00:22,600 --> 00:00:24,506
However, a tree is also a model of Sigma

9
00:00:24,606 --> 00:00:27,515
where we interpret E based on the direct-extension relation.

10
00:00:27,600 --> 00:00:30,966
Since if a extends b, and b extends c, then a must

11
00:00:31,066 --> 00:00:34,709
extend c. And no node is a direct extension of itself.

12
00:00:34,866 --> 00:00:37,086
And clearly, we can find a sentence chi to

13
00:00:37,186 --> 00:00:39,904
differentiate between a tree and a number line. For

14
00:00:40,004 --> 00:00:43,495
example, we could add this sentence, expressing totality, meaning

15
00:00:43,595 --> 00:00:46,312
that all elements are related by the edge relation.

16
00:00:46,400 --> 00:00:49,235
We see that our tree is not a model of this, since two

17
00:00:49,335 --> 00:00:53,692
different elements at the same level are not comparable by the extension relation.

18
00:00:53,733 --> 00:00:57,786
So, we could add chi as another axiom to our set Sigma.

19
00:00:57,866 --> 00:01:00,279
So Sigma now contains phi, psi, chi, and Mod

20
00:01:00,379 --> 00:01:02,677
Sigma is the set of linearly ordered sets.

21
00:01:02,800 --> 00:01:05,692
However, the theory of Sigma is still not complete,

22
00:01:05,792 --> 00:01:08,626
since for example both the natural numbers and the

23
00:01:08,726 --> 00:01:11,971
rational numbers satisfy these axioms under the less than

24
00:01:12,071 --> 00:01:15,492
relation, and we can differentiate the rational numbers from

25
00:01:15,592 --> 00:01:19,131
the natural numbers by this sentence theta expressing density.

26
00:01:19,200 --> 00:01:23,134
Meaning that for all x, y, if x is less than y, then there exists

27
00:01:23,234 --> 00:01:26,362
a z such that x is less than z and z is less than y.

28
00:01:26,400 --> 00:01:29,057
This is not true of the natural numbers, as there is

29
00:01:29,157 --> 00:01:31,655
no natural number in between 0 and 1 for example.

30
00:01:31,733 --> 00:01:34,281
However, given any fractional number, we can

31
00:01:34,381 --> 00:01:36,387
always find a number in between it.

32
00:01:37,000 --> 00:01:40,317
If we add theta to our set of axioms Sigma,

33
00:01:40,417 --> 00:01:44,450
and we add two more axioms expressing that there are

34
00:01:44,550 --> 00:01:48,106
no endpoints, then we get the theory of DLOWE.

35
00:01:48,266 --> 00:01:51,771
In 1895 Georg Cantor proved that all countable

36
00:01:51,871 --> 00:01:56,160
dense linear orderings without endpoints are isomorphic,

37
00:01:56,266 --> 00:01:59,528
which technically just means that there is an order

38
00:01:59,628 --> 00:02:03,550
preserving map between them, but essentially means that there

39
00:02:03,650 --> 00:02:06,847
is a unique countable set which satisfies this set

40
00:02:06,947 --> 00:02:10,011
of axioms, and this set is the rational numbers.

41
00:02:10,066 --> 00:02:12,696
So, this set of axioms here, is a close

42
00:02:12,796 --> 00:02:16,967
approximation of the structure of the fractional number line.

43
00:02:17,066 --> 00:02:21,082
However, it is not perfect as the real

44
00:02:21,182 --> 00:02:25,848
number line also satisfies the DLOWE axioms.

45
00:02:26,000 --> 00:02:29,639
But this set of axioms is as good as we can hope

46
00:02:29,739 --> 00:02:34,703
to do: Sigma is a complete axiomatization of the theory of DLOWE.

